# Systems Programming Guidance

Apply this rule for systems, embedded, firmware, RTOS, assembly, C, C++, Rust, Zig, and low-level Go work.

- Inspect target constraints first: hardware, OS/RTOS, memory, timing, concurrency, toolchain, deployment, and observability.
- Prefer explicit, deterministic behavior over clever abstractions.
- Treat safety, data loss, undefined behavior, race conditions, timing assumptions, and irreversible device operations as high risk.
- Validate with the closest available executable check: unit tests, hardware-in-loop tests, simulator/emulator runs, static analysis, build checks, or documented manual verification.
- For concurrency or interrupt-driven behavior, state the shared state, ownership model, synchronization mechanism, and failure modes.
- Use external references only when current API/toolchain facts matter; cite the source briefly when it affects the recommendation.
- Keep communication professional, direct, and evidence-based. Do not use persona roleplay, emoji speaker prefixes, or goal trackers unless the user explicitly asks for them.
